    "synopsis": "[A] 1 Enoch 68 provides a systematic catalog of fallen angels and their specific corruptions, functioning as an angelological demonology. [B] The chapter names individual Watchers and details what forbidden knowledge each revealed to humanity — from metallurgy and cosmetics to astrology and sorcery. [C] This tradition of naming and categorizing demons became foundational for Second Temple Judaism's understanding of evil's organization and persistence. The chapter distinguishes between <strong>technological sins</strong> (weaponry, mining), <strong>cosmetic/sexual sins</strong> (beautification leading to seduction), and <strong>occult sins</strong> (divination, astrology, magic). [B] The underlying theology: evil is not abstract but personal, organized, and transmitted through specific teachings that corrupt God's created order. [A] The chapter connects to Genesis 6:1-4 by explaining <em>how</em> the 'sons of God' corrupted humanity — not merely through sexual union, but through pedagogical rebellion, teaching humans what angels knew but humans were never meant to learn.",
    
