    "divine_council_note": "1 Enoch 68 reveals the dark inversion of the divine council's proper function. [B] In the legitimate council, God's agents (angels) execute his will and maintain cosmic order (Psalm 103:19-21, 148:2). [C] The Watchers represent a rogue faction within the council who chose to share council-level knowledge ('the secrets of heaven') with unauthorized recipients (humans). [A] This is precisely the sin described in Deuteronomy 29:29 — 'The secret things belong to YHWH our God, but the things revealed belong to us and our children.' [B] The Watchers violated the knowledge boundary between heaven and earth. Michael Heiser notes that the term 'sons of God' (bene elohim) always refers to divine council members in the OT (Job 1:6, 2:1, 38:7, Psalm 82:6, 89:6). [C] By naming each fallen angel and his specific teaching, 1 Enoch creates a demonic org chart — a shadow council that mirrors and opposes God's legitimate administration. This explains why spiritual warfare in the NT is described in terms of 'principalities and powers' (Ephesians 6:12) — organized hierarchies of evil corresponding to the Watcher rebellion.",
    
